member.example:
This code snippet shows you how to add a trace point to your code.
            iDB2Trace.Trace("MyMethod: Entered constructor");

           There are also Trace methods that do automatic string replacement.  The variable
           datatype can be any data type that can be converted to a string.
            if (iDB2Trace.Tracing)
                   iDB2Trace.Trace("MyMethod: Current datatype {0}", datatype);

           Another method allows you to do multiple string replacement by passing
           in an array of objects.  Also notice that the check to Tracing prevents
           the creation of an array of objects if tracing is not on.
            if (iDB2Trace.Tracing)
                   iDB2Trace.Trace("Current datatype {0}, length {1}",
                   new object[] { datatype, length });

           Logging is done in the same fashion as tracing, except you need to call
           the iDB2Trace.Logging method to check if logging is enabled and use one of the
           overloaded iDB2Trace.Log methods to write messages to the error log.
